It&#39;s a bear! Bringing video-based deep learning to the biodiversity of life

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Observing biodiversity is expensive and time-consuming. Ecologists are increasingly turning to long duration video to locate, count and identify animals in natural environments. However, scientists currently waste hundreds of hours manually watching and annotating frames. Automated video analysis using computer vision will increase the efficiency of ecological sampling and allow scientists to understand the effect of global change on biodiversity.

I will build a cloud platform for scientists to annotate animal presence in ecological videos. My project will utilize Google&#39;s newly announced [Cloud Video Intelligence API](https://cloud.google.com/video-intelligence/) for animal detection and massive parallelization. This will dramatically improve the reach, capability and functionality of my current desktop software for an engaged user community.

# Impact: What is this project doing for people? Does it create a lot of value for a few people or some value for a lot of people? How does our grant help enable progress?

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

This project will transform biological video analysis. I am currently the developer of [MotionMeerkat](http://benweinstein.weebly.com/motionmeerkat.html), an open source tool for animal detection in ecological videos (Fig. 1). Currently the videos are run serially, severely limiting the efficiency of analysis. The detector cannot determine animal identity, and it can be fooled by heavy wind and camera shake. Combining the new deep learning and cloud computing tools from Google will bring scalable machine learning for a new audience. This project will also be blueprint for cloud-based video monitoring for security, infrastructure, and business applications.

# Commitment: Why does this problem matter to you? Are you already working on it? What do you see as a &quot;success&quot; working on this project?

I have been passionate about this problem for five years. During my PhD, I worked to replace traditional ecological observation with video-based monitoring for biodiversity surveys. I have since gone to great lengths to learn a robust data science skillset in python, R, Git, Docker, and AWS. MotionMeerkat is a side-project, put together at night and on weekends.  The missing ingredient has been a state-of-the-art detector and web interface for greater power, flexibility and functionality.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 2. Project diagram: Phase I is a Youtube to Google Cloud transfer service that will allow users to tag videos to be analyzed. Phase II is a video processing service that finds animals in the video and returns key frames to the user. Phase III is a web platform to host user image annotations.

# Traction: What&#39;s the current state of the project? Who uses it and how? What do you think you&#39;ll be able to accomplish during the program?

Bringing this tool to the cloud will move past the battle of windows updates and video drivers that bog down installation. I am a beta tester for the Cloud Video Intelligence API and have terabytes of animal visitation videos to begin testing a range of use cases. I have tested Google&#39;s Machine Learning Engine for image classification using Tensorflow and received impressive results for optical character recognition.
